Furthermore, to determine the relationship between the concentration of the two ions and the degree of extraction, different amounts of Fe3+ and Hg2+ were introduced to NCQDs and BNCQD-5, respectively by progressively adding the two ions from 0 µL to 1000 µL (Fig. 7
                        ). For NCQDs, the detection limits (LOD) are 0.0161 and 0.0552 μM for Fe3+ (Fig. S8a) and Hg2+ (Fig. S8c), respectively, and the extraction quenching constants (Ksv) are 1.31 × 103 M−1 and 1.84 × 102 M−1, respectively. With a correlation value (R2) of 0.98, there is a strong linear correlation within the concentration range of 0–200 µL for Fe3+ and 20–200 µL for Hg2+. For both Fe3+ (Fig. S8b) and Hg2+ (Fig. S8b), the Ksv of BNCQD-5 are 1.25 × 103 M−1 and 1.25 × 102 M−1, respectively, while the LOD is 0.0199 and 0.111 μM. There is a good linear correlation with an R2 of 0.99, with a concentration range of 20–200 µL for Fe3+ and 0–200 µL for Hg2+. In comparison to previous studies, Tables 1
                         and S6 demonstrates its strong detection performance.
